        Jensen's slumped over the controls. Reed's against the far wall, thrown there by impact. Neither of them is moving.

        I say, "Jensen?"
        My voice comes out rough, too quiet. I try again, louder — "Reed?"

        Silence.

        I crawl to Jensen first. I press my fingers to his neck the way they show in the safety vids. Nothing. No pulse. His skin is cool. I check Reed too — have to, have to be sure — but I already know. Same stillness. Same silence. Same nothing.

        The rambling in my head stops. Just — stops. And there's only the quiet, and the smoke smell, and two people who died trying to save me.

        Jensen dragged me to the crash seat. He strapped me in himself and checked every buckle. He looked at me — actually looked at me.
        Jensen said, "Hold on, Voss."
        Almost kind, in the end.

        They knew. They put me in the safest spot on the ship and went back to die fighting for every second.

        I sit down hard, my back against the warped door.

        There should be someone talking — my AI, SAM. She should have been the first thing I heard when I woke up: damage assessment, vital signs, location data, a cheerful voice in my neural link helping me process. We've been partnered for two years. SAM was there when the pilots ignored me, when every station looked the same — a constant, friendly presence in the back of my mind.

        I reach for the link. I try to ping her.
        I say, "SAM?"

        The neural space where she lives feels empty. Wrong. Like reaching for something that should be in your pocket and finding nothing.

        I say, "SAM, are you there?"

        Silence. Not the comfortable silence of SAM listening, waiting to respond. Empty silence. The AI is gone — fried in the crash, or destroyed by whatever ripped through the ship's systems.

        Oh. Oh no.

        I press my hand against my temple like I could physically push her back into existence. Two years. She was — not just a tool, a companion. Someone who actually listened when I talked. And now she's gone. The pilots are gone. The ship is gone.

        I'm alone.
        ¶
        I sit there in the wreckage, first aid supplies scattered in my lap, and the full weight of it lands: injured, alone, unknown planet. No way to call for help — faster-than-light communication doesn't work like that — you can't just send a distress call across light-years. Rescue will come when we don't report in at our destination. That's — weeks? Months?

        Does anyone even know where we are?

        This is fine. This is... not fine. This is the opposite of fine.

        The adventure shows definitely didn't cover solo survival with head trauma and dead pilots and a fried AI. They covered teams. They covered heroes with training. They covered people who knew what they were doing.

        But I'm alive. Jensen and Reed aren't. SAM isn't.

        And I'm alive.

        Grief tries to surface — proper grief, the kind that wants to curl up and not move. I push it down. Later. Process later. Survive first.

        My hands are still shaking when I open the first aid kit: antiseptic, bandages, pressure pad for the leg wound. I talk myself through it, voice barely above a whisper.
      </text>
